§ Standard basis vectors ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Define $e_i ∈ 𝗥^n$ by $[e_i]_j = 1$ if $i = j$ and $0$
    otherwise. ⦉

  ‖ Then $e_1, e_2, …, e_n ∈ 𝗥^n$ are called the ❬standard
    basis vectors❭ (❬canonical basis vectors❭) for $𝗥^n$. ⦉

  ‖ For example, in $𝗥^3$,
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ e_1 = \bmat{1 ᜶ 0 ᜶ 0} ⦉
    ⦉⦉
⦉

